<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	ws-review-partial-derivatives.ptx
	Section 0 (Multivariable Calculus Review), worksheet R2:
	Partial Derivatives — first-order partials, the slope-of-a-trace
	interpretation, higher-order and mixed partials, and the total
	differential.

	Authored to the SHARED worksheet conventions
	(checklists/worksheet-conventions.md): paired component="stu"/"key"
	reading checks and exercises; one True/False misconception check; one
	read-along TikZ <latex-image> illustration (shown in both builds, no
	hidden content). Standard notation only (f_x, \partial f/\partial x) —
	no new macros. Book concepts are tracked but example equations are NOT
	reused.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-review-partial-derivatives">
	<title>Review: Partial Derivatives</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>Compute first-order partial derivatives by holding the other variable constant.</li>
			<li>Interpret a partial derivative as the slope of a trace and as a rate of change.</li>
			<li>Compute second-order and mixed partial derivatives, and recognize the equality of mixed partials.</li>
			<li>Use the total differential to estimate the change in a function.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: What is a partial derivative
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>I. Holding one variable fixed.</alert></p>

		<p>
			A function <m>f(x,y)</m> changes in two independent directions at
			once. To measure its rate of change in a single direction we freeze
			the other variable and fall back on ordinary one-variable
			differentiation. The <term>partial derivative</term> of <m>f</m>
			with respect to <m>x</m> is
			<md>
				f_x(x,y) = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}
				= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x+h,\,y) - f(x,y)}{h},
			</md>
			and <m>f_y</m> is defined the same way, perturbing <m>y</m> instead.
			In practice we never use the limit: to get <m>f_x</m>, treat
			<m>y</m> as a constant and differentiate in <m>x</m> with all the
			usual rules.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 1 -->
		<p component="stu">
			To compute <m>f_x</m> we treat <m>y</m> as a
			<fillin characters="9"/> <nbsp/>and differentiate with respect to
			<m>x</m>. The symbols <m>f_x</m>, <m>\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x}</m>,
			and <m>z_x</m> all mean the <fillin characters="5"/> <nbsp/>thing. We
			write <m>\partial</m> instead of <m>d</m> to signal that <m>f</m>
			depends on <fillin characters="12"/> <nbsp/>than one variable.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			To compute <m>f_x</m> we treat <m>y</m> as a
			<m>\underline{\textbf{constant}}</m> and differentiate with respect to
			<m>x</m>. The symbols <m>f_x</m>, <m>\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x}</m>,
			and <m>z_x</m> all mean the <m>\underline{\textbf{same}}</m> thing. We
			write <m>\partial</m> instead of <m>d</m> to signal that <m>f</m>
			depends on <m>\underline{\textbf{more}}</m> than one variable.
		</p>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: Computing first-order partials
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>II. Computing first-order partials.</alert></p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>f(x,y) = x^3 y - 2xy^2 + 5y</m>. Find <m>f_x</m> and
					<m>f_y</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>f(x,y) = x^3 y - 2xy^2 + 5y</m>. Find <m>f_x</m> and
					<m>f_y</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					For <m>f_x</m>, treat <m>y</m> as constant (so <m>5y</m> is a
					constant and drops out):
					<md>
						f_x = 3x^2 y - 2y^2.
					</md>
					For <m>f_y</m>, treat <m>x</m> as constant:
					<md>
						f_y = x^3 - 4xy + 5.
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><alert>Your turn.</alert> Watch for the product and chain rules — they still apply in the active variable.</p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find both first-order partial derivatives of each function.
					<ol>
						<li><m>g(x,y) = x\,e^{xy}</m></li>
						<li><m>h(x,y) = \sin(x^2 y)</m></li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find both first-order partial derivatives of each function.
					<ol>
						<li><m>g(x,y) = x\,e^{xy}</m></li>
						<li><m>h(x,y) = \sin(x^2 y)</m></li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<ol>
						<li>
							<m>g(x,y) = x\,e^{xy}</m>. In <m>x</m> this is a product
							(<m>x</m> times <m>e^{xy}</m>), and <m>e^{xy}</m> needs the
							chain rule with <m>y</m> held constant:
							<md>
								g_x = e^{xy} + x\,(y\,e^{xy}) = e^{xy}(1 + xy),
								\qquad g_y = x\,(x\,e^{xy}) = x^2 e^{xy}.
							</md>
						</li>
						<li>
							<m>h(x,y) = \sin(x^2 y)</m>, chain rule each time:
							<md>
								h_x = \cos(x^2 y)\cdot 2xy = 2xy\cos(x^2 y),
								\qquad h_y = \cos(x^2 y)\cdot x^2 = x^2\cos(x^2 y).
							</md>
						</li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: Geometric meaning (slope of a trace)
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>III. What a partial derivative measures.</alert></p>

		<p>
			Freezing <m>x=a</m> slices the surface <m>z=f(x,y)</m> with the
			plane <m>x=a</m>; the cut is a curve, the <term>trace</term>
			<m>z=f(a,y)</m>, living in that plane. The partial derivative
			<m>f_y(a,b)</m> is exactly the ordinary slope of this trace at
			<m>y=b</m> — the rate at which <m>f</m> climbs as we step in the
			<m>y</m>-direction from <m>(a,b)</m>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="ws-r2-fig-trace">
			<caption>Fixing <m>x=a</m> gives the trace <m>z=f(a,y)</m>;
				<m>f_y(a,b)</m> is its slope at <m>y=b</m>.</caption>
			<image width="60%">
				<shortdescription>A trace curve z equals f of a comma y plotted against y, with a straight tangent line drawn at the point where y equals b; the tangent's slope is labeled f sub y of a comma b.</shortdescription>
				<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}
	\begin{axis}[axis lines=middle, xmin=-0.5, xmax=4.5, ymin=-0.5, ymax=5,
		width=9cm, height=6cm, xlabel=$y$, ylabel=$z$,
		xtick={2}, xticklabels={$b$}, ytick=\empty,
		tick label style={font=\footnotesize}, clip=false]
	\addplot[domain=0:4, samples=80, thick, blue] {0.5*(x-1)^2 + 1};
	\addplot[domain=0.3:3.7, samples=2, thick, red] {1*(x-2) + 1.5};
	\addplot[only marks, mark=*, black, mark size=1.2pt] coordinates {(2,1.5)};
	\node[blue, anchor=south west, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:3.4,3.9) {$z=f(a,y)$};
	\node[red, anchor=north west, font=\footnotesize] at (axis cs:3.2,2.0) {slope $=f_y(a,b)$};
	\end{axis}
	\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<!-- reading-check pair 2 -->
		<p component="stu">
			If <m>f_x(a,b) &gt; 0</m>, then holding <m>y=b</m> and increasing
			<m>x</m> makes <m>f</m> <fillin characters="9"/>. If both
			<m>f_x(a,b)=0</m> and <m>f_y(a,b)=0</m>, the tangent plane at that
			point is <fillin characters="12"/>, which is why such points are
			candidates for maxima and minima.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			If <m>f_x(a,b) &gt; 0</m>, then holding <m>y=b</m> and increasing
			<m>x</m> makes <m>f</m> <m>\underline{\textbf{increase}}</m>. If both
			<m>f_x(a,b)=0</m> and <m>f_y(a,b)=0</m>, the tangent plane at that
			point is <m>\underline{\textbf{horizontal}}</m>, which is why such
			points are candidates for maxima and minima.
		</p>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 4: Higher-order and mixed partials
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>IV. Second-order and mixed partials.</alert></p>

		<p>
			Each partial derivative is itself a function of <m>x</m> and
			<m>y</m>, so we can differentiate again. The four second-order
			partials are <m>f_{xx}</m>, <m>f_{yy}</m>, and the two
			<term>mixed partials</term> <m>f_{xy}=(f_x)_y</m> and
			<m>f_{yx}=(f_y)_x</m>. Read the subscripts <em>left to right</em> in
			the order the derivatives are taken.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 3 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The mixed partial <m>f_{xy}</m> means: differentiate first with
			respect to <fillin characters="3"/>, then with respect to
			<fillin characters="3"/>. For every function we meet in this course,
			<m>f_{xy}</m> and <m>f_{yx}</m> come out <fillin characters="6"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The mixed partial <m>f_{xy}</m> means: differentiate first with
			respect to <m>\underline{\textbf{x}}</m>, then with respect to
			<m>\underline{\textbf{y}}</m>. For every function we meet in this
			course, <m>f_{xy}</m> and <m>f_{yx}</m> come out
			<m>\underline{\textbf{equal}}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For <m>f(x,y) = x^3 y - 2xy^2 + 5y</m> (the function from
					Part II), compute all four second-order partials
					<m>f_{xx}</m>, <m>f_{yy}</m>, <m>f_{xy}</m>, and
					<m>f_{yx}</m>. Verify that the mixed partials agree.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For <m>f(x,y) = x^3 y - 2xy^2 + 5y</m> (the function from
					Part II), compute all four second-order partials
					<m>f_{xx}</m>, <m>f_{yy}</m>, <m>f_{xy}</m>, and
					<m>f_{yx}</m>. Verify that the mixed partials agree.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Starting from <m>f_x = 3x^2 y - 2y^2</m> and
					<m>f_y = x^3 - 4xy + 5</m>:
					<md>
						f_{xx} = (f_x)_x = 6xy, \qquad
						f_{yy} = (f_y)_y = -4x,
					</md>
					<md>
						f_{xy} = (f_x)_y = 3x^2 - 4y, \qquad
						f_{yx} = (f_y)_x = 3x^2 - 4y.
					</md>
					The mixed partials agree: <m>f_{xy} = f_{yx} = 3x^2 - 4y</m>,
					as the equality of mixed partials promises.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<!-- misconception check: single exercise, solution instructor-only -->
		<exercise xml:id="ws-r2-tf-order">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<alert>True or False.</alert> The mixed partial <m>f_{xy}</m> is
					computed by differentiating first with respect to <m>y</m>, then
					with respect to <m>x</m>. Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					<term>False.</term> Subscript notation is read left to right:
					<m>f_{xy} = (f_x)_y</m> means differentiate with respect to
					<m>x</m> first, then <m>y</m>. (The Leibniz form
					<m>\dfrac{\partial^2 f}{\partial y\,\partial x}</m> stacks the
					same two steps in the opposite written order, which is exactly
					what trips people up.) Because the mixed partials are equal for
					our functions, the final answer is the same either way — but the
					<em>reasoning</em> about order should still be correct.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 5: The total differential (application) + looking ahead
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>V. Estimating change: the total differential.</alert></p>

		<p>
			Partial derivatives combine into a single linear estimate of how
			<m>f</m> responds to small moves in <em>both</em> inputs at once. The
			<term>total differential</term> of <m>z=f(x,y)</m> is
			<md>
				dz = f_x\,dx + f_y\,dy,
			</md>
			and for small changes <m>dx</m>, <m>dy</m> the actual change
			<m>\Delta z</m> is approximately <m>dz</m>. Each partial says how
			much its own variable contributes.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 4 -->
		<p component="stu">
			In <m>dz = f_x\,dx + f_y\,dy</m>, the term <m>f_x\,dx</m> is the
			change in <m>z</m> due to moving <m>x</m> alone, and the whole
			expression <fillin characters="15"/> <nbsp/>the true change
			<m>\Delta z</m> when <m>dx</m> and <m>dy</m> are
			<fillin characters="6"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			In <m>dz = f_x\,dx + f_y\,dy</m>, the term <m>f_x\,dx</m> is the
			change in <m>z</m> due to moving <m>x</m> alone, and the whole
			expression <m>\underline{\textbf{approximates}}</m> the true change
			<m>\Delta z</m> when <m>dx</m> and <m>dy</m> are
			<m>\underline{\textbf{small}}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- application (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A closed cylindrical can has volume <m>V(r,h) = \pi r^2 h</m>.
					A run of cans is manufactured with radius <m>r = 3</m> cm and
					height <m>h = 10</m> cm, but the machine's tolerance lets each
					drift by up to <m>dr = 0.05</m> cm and <m>dh = 0.1</m> cm. Use
					the total differential to estimate the largest resulting change
					in volume.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A closed cylindrical can has volume <m>V(r,h) = \pi r^2 h</m>.
					A run of cans is manufactured with radius <m>r = 3</m> cm and
					height <m>h = 10</m> cm, but the machine's tolerance lets each
					drift by up to <m>dr = 0.05</m> cm and <m>dh = 0.1</m> cm. Use
					the total differential to estimate the largest resulting change
					in volume.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The partials are <m>V_r = 2\pi r h</m> and <m>V_h = \pi r^2</m>,
					so
					<md>
						dV = 2\pi r h\,dr + \pi r^2\,dh.
					</md>
					At <m>(r,h)=(3,10)</m>: <m>V_r = 60\pi</m> and
					<m>V_h = 9\pi</m>. Taking both drifts positive to maximize the
					change,
					<md>
						dV = 60\pi(0.05) + 9\pi(0.1) = 3\pi + 0.9\pi = 3.9\pi
						\approx 12.25 \text{ cm}^3.
					</md>
					So volumes vary by roughly <m>\pm 12</m> cm<m>^3</m>. Notice the
					radius term dominates — because <m>V</m> depends on <m>r^2</m>,
					the can's volume is far more sensitive to a wobble in radius
					than in height.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<conclusion>
		<p>
			<alert>Looking ahead.</alert> Partial derivatives are the raw
			material for everything that follows. Collected into a vector they
			form the <term>gradient</term> <m>\nabla f = \langle f_x, f_y\rangle</m>,
			which points in the direction of steepest increase; chained together
			they track how <m>f</m> changes along a moving path (the multivariable
			chain rule); and integrated in reverse they will let us recover
			functions from their rates of change. Next we review
			<term>double integrals</term>, the other half of the multivariable
			toolkit.
		</p>
	</conclusion>

</worksheet>
